Its most efficient form is the wild root taken with wine. Authorities add that this root is more efficacious if the draught be taken out of doors. Pythagoras divided rue also into (a) male, with smaller leaves and of a grass—green colom, and (b) female, with more luxuriant leaves and more colour. He also thought it injurious to the eyes, wrongly, since. engi-avers and painters use rue as fuod, with bread or cress, for the sake of their eyes; wild goats also, they say, eat it to improve their vision. Many have dispelled dimness by anointing the eyes with its juice added to Attic l.‹›ney or to the milk of a woman who has just borne a inale child, or even by tonehing the corners of the eyes with the pure juice.
